Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.name: accelerateModeEnabled
Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.abstract: Returns whether the client has enabled accelerate mode for getting and putting objects. The default is NO.

Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.name: HTTPMethod
Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.abstract: Specifies the verb used in the pre-signed URL. accepted AWSHTTPMethodGET, AWSHTTPMethodPUT, AWSHTTPMethodHEAD.

Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.name: expires
Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.abstract: The time when the signature expires, specified as an NSDate object.

Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.name: minimumCredentialsExpirationInterval
Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.abstract: AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest will automatically refresh temporary credential if expiration duration in less than minimumCredentialsExpirationInterval. Only applied for credential provider using temporary token (e.g. CognitoIdentityProvider). Default value is 3000 seconds.

Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.name: contentType
Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.abstract: Expected content-type of the request. If set, the content-type will be included in the signature and future requests must include the same content-type header value to access the presigned URL. This parameter is ignored unless AWSHTTPMethod is equal to AWSHTTPMethodPUT. Default is nil.

Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.name: contentMD5
Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.abstract: Expected content-md5 header of the request. If set, this header value will be included when calculating the signature and future requests must include the same content-md5 header value to access the presigned URL. This parameter is ignored unless HTTPMethod is equal to AWSHTTPMethodPUT. Default is nil.

Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.name: requestHeaders
Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.abstract: This NSDictionary can contains additional request headers to be included in the pre-signed URL. Default is emtpy.

Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.name: requestParameters
Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.abstract: This NSDictionary can contains additional request parameters to be included in the pre-signed URL. Adding additional request parameters enables more advanced pre-signed URLs, such as accessing Amazon S3’s torrent resource for an object, or for specifying a version ID when accessing an object. Default is emtpy.

Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.name: -setValue:forRequestHeader:
Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.abstract: Set an additional request header to be included in the pre-signed URL.

Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.name: -setValue:forRequestParameter:
Classes/AWSS3GetPreSignedURLRequest.html.abstract: Set an additional request parameter to be included in the pre-signed URL. Adding additional request parameters enables more advanced pre-signed URLs, such as accessing Amazon S3’s torrent resource for an object, or for specifying a version ID when accessing an object.

Classes/AWSS3PreSignedURLBuilder.html#/c.name: +defaultS3PreSignedURLBuilder
Classes/AWSS3PreSignedURLBuilder.html#/c.abstract: Returns the singleton service client. If the singleton object does not exist, the SDK instantiates the default service client with defaultServiceConfiguration from [AWSServiceManager defaultServiceManager]. The reference to this object is maintained by the SDK, and you do not need to retain it manually.

Classes/AWSS3PreSignedURLBuilder.html#/c.name: +registerS3PreSignedURLBuilderWithConfiguration:forKey:
Classes/AWSS3PreSignedURLBuilder.html#/c.abstract: Creates a service client with the given service configuration and registers it for the key.

Classes/AWSS3PreSignedURLBuilder.html#/c.name: +S3PreSignedURLBuilderForKey:
Classes/AWSS3PreSignedURLBuilder.html#/c.abstract: Retrieves the service client associated with the key. You need to call + registerS3PreSignedURLBuilderWithConfiguration:forKey: before invoking this method.

Classes/AWSS3PreSignedURLBuilder.html#/c.name: +removeS3PreSignedURLBuilderForKey:
Classes/AWSS3PreSignedURLBuilder.html#/c.abstract: Removes the service client associated with the key and release it.

Classes/AWSS3PreSignedURLBuilder.html#/c.name: -getPreSignedURL:
Classes/AWSS3PreSignedURLBuilder.html#/c.abstract: Build a time-limited pre-signed URL to get object from S3, return nil if build process failed.

Classes/AWSS3WebsiteConfiguration.html#/.name: errorDocument
Classes/AWSS3WebsiteConfiguration.html#/.abstract: The name of the error document for the website.

Classes/AWSS3WebsiteConfiguration.html#/.name: indexDocument
Classes/AWSS3WebsiteConfiguration.html#/.abstract: The name of the index document for the website.

Classes/AWSS3WebsiteConfiguration.html#/.name: redirectAllRequestsTo
Classes/AWSS3WebsiteConfiguration.html#/.abstract:
The redirect behavior for every request to this bucket’s website endpoint.

If you specify this property, you can’t specify any other property.

Classes/AWSS3WebsiteConfiguration.html#/.name: routingRules
Classes/AWSS3WebsiteConfiguration.html#/.abstract: Rules that define when a redirect is applied and the redirect behavior.

Classes/AWSS3VersioningConfiguration.htm.name: MFADelete
Classes/AWSS3VersioningConfiguration.htm.abstract: Specifies whether MFA delete is enabled in the bucket versioning configuration. This element is only returned if the bucket has been configured with MFA delete. If the bucket has never been so configured, this element is not returned.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.name: bucket
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.abstract:
The name of the bucket to which the multipart upload was initiated.

When using this API with an access point, you must direct requests to the access point hostname. The access point hostname takes the form AccessPointName-AccountId.s3-accesspoint.Region.amazonaws.com. When using this operation with an access point through the AWS SDKs, you provide the access point ARN in place of the bucket name. For more information about access point ARNs, see Using Access Points in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

When using this API with Amazon S3 on Outposts, you must direct requests to the S3 on Outposts hostname. The S3 on Outposts hostname takes the form AccessPointName-AccountId.outpostID.s3-outposts.Region.amazonaws.com. When using this operation using S3 on Outposts through the AWS SDKs, you provide the Outposts bucket ARN in place of the bucket name. For more information about S3 on Outposts ARNs, see Using S3 on Outposts in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.name: contentLength
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.abstract: Size of the body in bytes. This parameter is useful when the size of the body cannot be determined automatically.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.name: contentMD5
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.abstract: The base64-encoded 128-bit MD5 digest of the part data. This parameter is auto-populated when using the command from the CLI. This parameter is required if object lock parameters are specified.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.name: expectedBucketOwner
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.abstract: The account id of the expected bucket owner. If the bucket is owned by a different account, the request will fail with an HTTP 403 (Access Denied) error.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.name: key
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.abstract: Object key for which the multipart upload was initiated.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.name: partNumber
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.abstract: Part number of part being uploaded. This is a positive integer between 1 and 10,000.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.name: requestPayer
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.abstract: Confirms that the requester knows that they will be charged for the request. Bucket owners need not specify this parameter in their requests. For information about downloading objects from requester pays buckets, see Downloading Objects in Requestor Pays Buckets in the Amazon S3 Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.name: SSECustomerAlgorithm
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.abstract: Specifies the algorithm to use to when encrypting the object (for example, AES256).

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.name: SSECustomerKey
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.abstract: Specifies the customer-provided encryption key for Amazon S3 to use in encrypting data. This value is used to store the object and then it is discarded; Amazon S3 does not store the encryption key. The key must be appropriate for use with the algorithm specified in the x-amz-server-side-encryption-customer-algorithm header. This must be the same encryption key specified in the initiate multipart upload request.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.name: SSECustomerKeyMD5
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.abstract: Specifies the 128-bit MD5 digest of the encryption key according to RFC 1321. Amazon S3 uses this header for a message integrity check to ensure that the encryption key was transmitted without error.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.name: uploadId
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartRequest.html#/c:o.abstract: Upload ID identifying the multipart upload whose part is being uploaded.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartOutput.html#/c:ob.name: requestCharged
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartOutput.html#/c:ob.abstract: If present, indicates that the requester was successfully charged for the request.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartOutput.html#/c:ob.name: SSECustomerAlgorithm
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartOutput.html#/c:ob.abstract: If server-side encryption with a customer-provided encryption key was requested, the response will include this header confirming the encryption algorithm used.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartOutput.html#/c:ob.name: SSECustomerKeyMD5
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartOutput.html#/c:ob.abstract: If server-side encryption with a customer-provided encryption key was requested, the response will include this header to provide round-trip message integrity verification of the customer-provided encryption key.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartOutput.html#/c:ob.name: SSEKMSKeyId
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartOutput.html#/c:ob.abstract: If present, specifies the ID of the AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) symmetric customer managed customer master key (CMK) was used for the object.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartOutput.html#/c:ob.name: serverSideEncryption
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartOutput.html#/c:ob.abstract: The server-side encryption algorithm used when storing this object in Amazon S3 (for example, AES256, aws:kms).

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: bucket
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract:
The bucket name.

When using this API with an access point, you must direct requests to the access point hostname. The access point hostname takes the form AccessPointName-AccountId.s3-accesspoint.Region.amazonaws.com. When using this operation with an access point through the AWS SDKs, you provide the access point ARN in place of the bucket name. For more information about access point ARNs, see Using Access Points in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

When using this API with Amazon S3 on Outposts, you must direct requests to the S3 on Outposts hostname. The S3 on Outposts hostname takes the form AccessPointName-AccountId.outpostID.s3-outposts.Region.amazonaws.com. When using this operation using S3 on Outposts through the AWS SDKs, you provide the Outposts bucket ARN in place of the bucket name. For more information about S3 on Outposts ARNs, see Using S3 on Outposts in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: replicateSource
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract:
Specifies the source object for the copy operation. You specify the value in one of two formats, depending on whether you want to access the source object through an access point:

  • For objects not accessed through an access point, specify the name of the source bucket and key of the source object, separated by a slash (/). For example, to copy the object reports/january.pdf from the bucket awsexamplebucket, use awsexamplebucket/reports/january.pdf. The value must be URL encoded.

  • For objects accessed through access points, specify the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the object as accessed through the access point, in the format arn:aws:s3:<Region>:<account-id>:accesspoint/<access-point-name>/object/<key>. For example, to copy the object reports/january.pdf through access point my-access-point owned by account 123456789012 in Region us-west-2, use the URL encoding of arn:aws:s3:us-west-2:123456789012:accesspoint/my-access-point/object/reports/january.pdf. The value must be URL encoded.

    Amazon S3 supports copy operations using access points only when the source and destination buckets are in the same AWS Region.

    Alternatively, for objects accessed through Amazon S3 on Outposts, specify the ARN of the object as accessed in the format arn:aws:s3-outposts:<Region>:<account-id>:outpost/<outpost-id>/object/<key>. For example, to copy the object reports/january.pdf through outpost my-outpost owned by account 123456789012 in Region us-west-2, use the URL encoding of arn:aws:s3-outposts:us-west-2:123456789012:outpost/my-outpost/object/reports/january.pdf. The value must be URL encoded.

To copy a specific version of an object, append ?versionId=<version-id> to the value (for example, awsexamplebucket/reports/january.pdf?versionId=QUpfdndhfd8438MNFDN93jdnJFkdmqnh893). If you don’t specify a version ID, Amazon S3 copies the latest version of the source object.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: replicateSourceIfMatch
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Copies the object if its entity tag (ETag) matches the specified tag.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: replicateSourceIfModifiedSince
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Copies the object if it has been modified since the specified time.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: replicateSourceIfNoneMatch
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Copies the object if its entity tag (ETag) is different than the specified ETag.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: replicateSourceIfUnmodifiedSince
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Copies the object if it hasn’t been modified since the specified time.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: replicateSourceRange
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: The range of bytes to copy from the source object. The range value must use the form bytes=first-last, where the first and last are the zero-based byte offsets to copy. For example, bytes=0-9 indicates that you want to copy the first 10 bytes of the source. You can copy a range only if the source object is greater than 5 MB.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: replicateSourceSSECustomerAlgorithm
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Specifies the algorithm to use when decrypting the source object (for example, AES256).

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: replicateSourceSSECustomerKey
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Specifies the customer-provided encryption key for Amazon S3 to use to decrypt the source object. The encryption key provided in this header must be one that was used when the source object was created.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: replicateSourceSSECustomerKeyMD5
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Specifies the 128-bit MD5 digest of the encryption key according to RFC 1321. Amazon S3 uses this header for a message integrity check to ensure that the encryption key was transmitted without error.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: expectedBucketOwner
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: The account id of the expected destination bucket owner. If the destination bucket is owned by a different account, the request will fail with an HTTP 403 (Access Denied) error.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: expectedSourceBucketOwner
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: The account id of the expected source bucket owner. If the source bucket is owned by a different account, the request will fail with an HTTP 403 (Access Denied) error.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: key
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Object key for which the multipart upload was initiated.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: partNumber
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Part number of part being copied. This is a positive integer between 1 and 10,000.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: requestPayer
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Confirms that the requester knows that they will be charged for the request. Bucket owners need not specify this parameter in their requests. For information about downloading objects from requester pays buckets, see Downloading Objects in Requestor Pays Buckets in the Amazon S3 Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: SSECustomerAlgorithm
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Specifies the algorithm to use to when encrypting the object (for example, AES256).

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: SSECustomerKey
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Specifies the customer-provided encryption key for Amazon S3 to use in encrypting data. This value is used to store the object and then it is discarded; Amazon S3 does not store the encryption key. The key must be appropriate for use with the algorithm specified in the x-amz-server-side-encryption-customer-algorithm header. This must be the same encryption key specified in the initiate multipart upload request.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: SSECustomerKeyMD5
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Specifies the 128-bit MD5 digest of the encryption key according to RFC 1321. Amazon S3 uses this header for a message integrity check to ensure that the encryption key was transmitted without error.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.name: uploadId
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyRequest.html#.abstract: Upload ID identifying the multipart upload whose part is being copied.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyOutput.html#/.name: replicateSourceVersionId
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyOutput.html#/.abstract: The version of the source object that was copied, if you have enabled versioning on the source bucket.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyOutput.html#/.name: requestCharged
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyOutput.html#/.abstract: If present, indicates that the requester was successfully charged for the request.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyOutput.html#/.name: SSECustomerAlgorithm
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyOutput.html#/.abstract: If server-side encryption with a customer-provided encryption key was requested, the response will include this header confirming the encryption algorithm used.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyOutput.html#/.name: SSECustomerKeyMD5
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyOutput.html#/.abstract: If server-side encryption with a customer-provided encryption key was requested, the response will include this header to provide round-trip message integrity verification of the customer-provided encryption key.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyOutput.html#/.name: SSEKMSKeyId
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyOutput.html#/.abstract: If present, specifies the ID of the AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) symmetric customer managed customer master key (CMK) that was used for the object.

Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyOutput.html#/.name: serverSideEncryption
Classes/AWSS3UploadPartCopyOutput.html#/.abstract: The server-side encryption algorithm used when storing this object in Amazon S3 (for example, AES256, aws:kms).

Classes/AWSS3Transition.html#/c:objc(cs).name: date
Classes/AWSS3Transition.html#/c:objc(cs).abstract: Indicates when objects are transitioned to the specified storage class. The date value must be in ISO 8601 format. The time is always midnight UTC.

Classes/AWSS3Transition.html#/c:objc(cs).name: days
Classes/AWSS3Transition.html#/c:objc(cs).abstract: Indicates the number of days after creation when objects are transitioned to the specified storage class. The value must be a positive integer.

Classes/AWSS3Transition.html#/c:objc(cs).name: storageClass
Classes/AWSS3Transition.html#/c:objc(cs).abstract: The storage class to which you want the object to transition.

Classes/AWSS3TopicConfigurationDeprecate.name: event
Classes/AWSS3TopicConfigurationDeprecate.abstract: Bucket event for which to send notifications.

Classes/AWSS3TopicConfigurationDeprecate.name: events
Classes/AWSS3TopicConfigurationDeprecate.abstract: A collection of events related to objects

Classes/AWSS3TopicConfigurationDeprecate.name: identifier
Classes/AWSS3TopicConfigurationDeprecate.abstract: An optional unique identifier for configurations in a notification configuration. If you don’t provide one, Amazon S3 will assign an ID.

Classes/AWSS3TopicConfigurationDeprecate.name: topic
Classes/AWSS3TopicConfigurationDeprecate.abstract: Amazon SNS topic to which Amazon S3 will publish a message to report the specified events for the bucket.

Classes/AWSS3TopicConfiguration.html#/c:.name: events
Classes/AWSS3TopicConfiguration.html#/c:.abstract: The Amazon S3 bucket event about which to send notifications. For more information, see Supported Event Types in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3TopicConfiguration.html#/c:.name: filter
Classes/AWSS3TopicConfiguration.html#/c:.abstract: Specifies object key name filtering rules. For information about key name filtering, see Configuring Event Notifications in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3TopicConfiguration.html#/c:.name: identifier
Classes/AWSS3TopicConfiguration.html#/c:.abstract: An optional unique identifier for configurations in a notification configuration. If you don’t provide one, Amazon S3 will assign an ID.

Classes/AWSS3TopicConfiguration.html#/c:.name: topicArn
Classes/AWSS3TopicConfiguration.html#/c:.abstract: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the Amazon SNS topic to which Amazon S3 publishes a message when it detects events of the specified type.

Classes/AWSS3TargetGrant.html#/c:objc(cs.name: grantee
Classes/AWSS3TargetGrant.html#/c:objc(cs.abstract: Container for the person being granted permissions.

Classes/AWSS3TargetGrant.html#/c:objc(cs.name: permission
Classes/AWSS3TargetGrant.html#/c:objc(cs.abstract: Logging permissions assigned to the grantee for the bucket.

Classes/AWSS3Tagging.html#/c:objc(cs)AWS.name: tagSet
Classes/AWSS3Tagging.html#/c:objc(cs)AWS.abstract: A collection for a set of tags

Classes/AWSS3StorageClassAnalysisDataExp.name: destination
Classes/AWSS3StorageClassAnalysisDataExp.abstract: The place to store the data for an analysis.

Classes/AWSS3StorageClassAnalysisDataExp.name: outputSchemaVersion
Classes/AWSS3StorageClassAnalysisDataExp.abstract: The version of the output schema to use when exporting data. Must be V_1.

Classes/AWSS3StorageClassAnalysis.html#/.name: dataExport
Classes/AWSS3StorageClassAnalysis.html#/.abstract: Specifies how data related to the storage class analysis for an Amazon S3 bucket should be exported.

Classes/AWSS3Stats.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3.name: bytesProcessed
Classes/AWSS3Stats.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3.abstract: The total number of uncompressed object bytes processed.

Classes/AWSS3Stats.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3.name: bytesReturned
Classes/AWSS3Stats.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3.abstract: The total number of bytes of records payload data returned.

Classes/AWSS3Stats.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3.name: bytesScanned
Classes/AWSS3Stats.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3.abstract: The total number of object bytes scanned.

Classes/AWSS3SseKmsEncryptedObjects.html.name: status
Classes/AWSS3SseKmsEncryptedObjects.html.abstract: Specifies whether Amazon S3 replicates objects created with server-side encryption using a customer master key (CMK) stored in AWS Key Management Service.

Classes/AWSS3SourceSelectionCriteria.htm.name: sseKmsEncryptedObjects
Classes/AWSS3SourceSelectionCriteria.htm.abstract: A container for filter information for the selection of Amazon S3 objects encrypted with AWS KMS. If you include SourceSelectionCriteria in the replication configuration, this element is required.

Classes/AWSS3ServerSideEncryptionRule.ht.name: applyServerSideEncryptionByDefault
Classes/AWSS3ServerSideEncryptionRule.ht.abstract: Specifies the default server-side encryption to apply to new objects in the bucket. If a PUT Object request doesn’t specify any server-side encryption, this default encryption will be applied.

Classes/AWSS3ServerSideEncryptionConfigu.name: rules
Classes/AWSS3ServerSideEncryptionConfigu.abstract: Container for information about a particular server-side encryption configuration rule.

Classes/AWSS3ServerSideEncryptionByDefau.name: KMSMasterKeyID
Classes/AWSS3ServerSideEncryptionByDefau.abstract:
AWS Key Management Service (KMS) customer master key ID to use for the default encryption. This parameter is allowed if and only if SSEAlgorithm is set to aws:kms.

You can specify the key ID or the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the CMK. However, if you are using encryption with cross-account operations, you must use a fully qualified CMK ARN. For more information, see Using encryption for cross-account operations.

For example:

  • Key ID: 1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab

  • Key ARN: arn:aws:kms:us-east-2:111122223333:key/1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab

Amazon S3 only supports symmetric CMKs and not asymmetric CMKs. For more information, see Using Symmetric and Asymmetric Keys in the AWS Key Management Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3ServerSideEncryptionByDefau.name: SSEAlgorithm
Classes/AWSS3ServerSideEncryptionByDefau.abstract: Server-side encryption algorithm to use for the default encryption.

Classes/AWSS3SelectParameters.html#/c:ob.name: expression
Classes/AWSS3SelectParameters.html#/c:ob.abstract: The expression that is used to query the object.

Classes/AWSS3SelectParameters.html#/c:ob.name: expressionType
Classes/AWSS3SelectParameters.html#/c:ob.abstract: The type of the provided expression (for example, SQL).

Classes/AWSS3SelectParameters.html#/c:ob.name: inputSerialization
Classes/AWSS3SelectParameters.html#/c:ob.abstract: Describes the serialization format of the object.

Classes/AWSS3SelectParameters.html#/c:ob.name: outputSerialization
Classes/AWSS3SelectParameters.html#/c:ob.abstract: Describes how the results of the Select job are serialized.

Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..name: expectedBucketOwner
Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..abstract: The account id of the expected bucket owner. If the bucket is owned by a different account, the request will fail with an HTTP 403 (Access Denied) error.

Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..name: expression
Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..abstract: The expression that is used to query the object.

Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..name: expressionType
Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..abstract: The type of the provided expression (for example, SQL).

Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..name: inputSerialization
Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..abstract: Describes the format of the data in the object that is being queried.

Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..name: outputSerialization
Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..abstract: Describes the format of the data that you want Amazon S3 to return in response.

Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..name: requestProgress
Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..abstract: Specifies if periodic request progress information should be enabled.

Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..name: SSECustomerAlgorithm
Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..abstract: The SSE Algorithm used to encrypt the object. For more information, see Server-Side Encryption (Using Customer-Provided Encryption Keys.

Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..name: SSECustomerKey
Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..abstract: The SSE Customer Key. For more information, see Server-Side Encryption (Using Customer-Provided Encryption Keys.

Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..name: SSECustomerKeyMD5
Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..abstract: The SSE Customer Key MD5. For more information, see Server-Side Encryption (Using Customer-Provided Encryption Keys.

Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..name: scanRange
Classes/AWSS3SelectObjectContentRequest..abstract:
Specifies the byte range of the object to get the records from. A record is processed when its first byte is contained by the range. This parameter is optional, but when specified, it must not be empty. See RFC 2616, Section 14.35.1 about how to specify the start and end of the range.

ScanRangemay be used in the following ways:

  • <scanrange><start>50</start><end>100</end></scanrange> - process only the records starting between the bytes 50 and 100 (inclusive, counting from zero)

  • <scanrange><start>50</start></scanrange> - process only the records starting after the byte 50

  • <scanrange><end>50</end></scanrange> - process only the records within the last 50 bytes of the file.

Classes/AWSS3ScanRange.html#/c:objc(cs)A.name: end
Classes/AWSS3ScanRange.html#/c:objc(cs)A.abstract: Specifies the end of the byte range. This parameter is optional. Valid values: non-negative integers. The default value is one less than the size of the object being queried. If only the End parameter is supplied, it is interpreted to mean scan the last N bytes of the file. For example, <scanrange><end>50</end></scanrange> means scan the last 50 bytes.

Classes/AWSS3ScanRange.html#/c:objc(cs)A.name: start
Classes/AWSS3ScanRange.html#/c:objc(cs)A.abstract: Specifies the start of the byte range. This parameter is optional. Valid values: non-negative integers. The default value is 0. If only start is supplied, it means scan from that point to the end of the file.For example; <scanrange><start>50</start></scanrange> means scan from byte 50 until the end of the file.

Classes/AWSS3SSEKMS.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS.name: keyId
Classes/AWSS3SSEKMS.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS.abstract: Specifies the ID of the AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) symmetric customer managed customer master key (CMK) to use for encrypting inventory reports.

Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).name: accessControlList
Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).abstract: A list of grants that control access to the staged results.

Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).name: bucketName
Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).abstract: The name of the bucket where the restore results will be placed.

Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).name: cannedACL
Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).abstract: The canned ACL to apply to the restore results.

Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).name: encryption
Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).abstract: Contains the type of server-side encryption used.

Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).name: prefix
Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).abstract: The prefix that is prepended to the restore results for this request.

Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).name: storageClass
Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).abstract: The class of storage used to store the restore results.

Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).name: tagging
Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).abstract: The tag-set that is applied to the restore results.

Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).name: userMetadata
Classes/AWSS3S3Location.html#/c:objc(cs).abstract: A list of metadata to store with the restore results in S3.

Classes/AWSS3S3KeyFilter.html#/c:objc(cs.name: filterRules
Classes/AWSS3S3KeyFilter.html#/c:objc(cs.abstract: A list of containers for the key-value pair that defines the criteria for the filter rule.

Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.name: abortIncompleteMultipartUpload
Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.abstract: Specifies the days since the initiation of an incomplete multipart upload that Amazon S3 will wait before permanently removing all parts of the upload. For more information, see Aborting Incomplete Multipart Uploads Using a Bucket Lifecycle Policy in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.name: expiration
Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.abstract: Specifies the expiration for the lifecycle of the object.

Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.name: identifier
Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.abstract: Unique identifier for the rule. The value can’t be longer than 255 characters.

Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.name: noncurrentVersionExpiration
Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.abstract: Specifies when noncurrent object versions expire. Upon expiration, Amazon S3 permanently deletes the noncurrent object versions. You set this lifecycle configuration action on a bucket that has versioning enabled (or suspended) to request that Amazon S3 delete noncurrent object versions at a specific period in the object’s lifetime.

Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.name: noncurrentVersionTransition
Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.abstract: Container for the transition rule that describes when noncurrent objects transition to the STANDARD_IA, ONEZONE_IA, INTELLIGENT_TIERING, GLACIER, or DEEP_ARCHIVE storage class. If your bucket is versioning-enabled (or versioning is suspended), you can set this action to request that Amazon S3 transition noncurrent object versions to the STANDARD_IA, ONEZONE_IA, INTELLIGENT_TIERING, GLACIER, or DEEP_ARCHIVE storage class at a specific period in the object’s lifetime.

Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.name: prefix
Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.abstract: Object key prefix that identifies one or more objects to which this rule applies.

Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.name: status
Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.abstract: If Enabled, the rule is currently being applied. If Disabled, the rule is not currently being applied.

Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.name: transition
Classes/AWSS3Rule.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS3R.abstract: Specifies when an object transitions to a specified storage class. For more information about Amazon S3 lifecycle configuration rules, see Transitioning Objects Using Amazon S3 Lifecycle in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3RoutingRule.html#/c:objc(cs.name: condition
Classes/AWSS3RoutingRule.html#/c:objc(cs.abstract: A container for describing a condition that must be met for the specified redirect to apply. For example, 1. If request is for pages in the /docs folder, redirect to the /documents folder. 2. If request results in HTTP error 4xx, redirect request to another host where you might process the error.

Classes/AWSS3RoutingRule.html#/c:objc(cs.name: redirect
Classes/AWSS3RoutingRule.html#/c:objc(cs.abstract: Container for redirect information. You can redirect requests to another host, to another page, or with another protocol. In the event of an error, you can specify a different error code to return.

Classes/AWSS3RestoreRequest.html#/c:objc.name: days
Classes/AWSS3RestoreRequest.html#/c:objc.abstract: Lifetime of the active copy in days. Do not use with restores that specify OutputLocation.

Classes/AWSS3RestoreRequest.html#/c:objc.name: glacierJobParameters
Classes/AWSS3RestoreRequest.html#/c:objc.abstract: S3 Glacier related parameters pertaining to this job. Do not use with restores that specify OutputLocation.

Classes/AWSS3RestoreRequest.html#/c:objc.name: outputLocation
Classes/AWSS3RestoreRequest.html#/c:objc.abstract: Describes the location where the restore job’s output is stored.

Classes/AWSS3RestoreRequest.html#/c:objc.name: selectParameters
Classes/AWSS3RestoreRequest.html#/c:objc.abstract: Describes the parameters for Select job types.

Classes/AWSS3RestoreRequest.html#/c:objc.name: tier
Classes/AWSS3RestoreRequest.html#/c:objc.abstract: S3 Glacier retrieval tier at which the restore will be processed.

Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectRequest.html#/.name: bucket
Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectRequest.html#/.abstract:
The bucket name or containing the object to restore.

When using this API with an access point, you must direct requests to the access point hostname. The access point hostname takes the form AccessPointName-AccountId.s3-accesspoint.Region.amazonaws.com. When using this operation with an access point through the AWS SDKs, you provide the access point ARN in place of the bucket name. For more information about access point ARNs, see Using Access Points in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

When using this API with Amazon S3 on Outposts, you must direct requests to the S3 on Outposts hostname. The S3 on Outposts hostname takes the form AccessPointName-AccountId.outpostID.s3-outposts.Region.amazonaws.com. When using this operation using S3 on Outposts through the AWS SDKs, you provide the Outposts bucket ARN in place of the bucket name. For more information about S3 on Outposts ARNs, see Using S3 on Outposts in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectRequest.html#/.name: expectedBucketOwner
Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectRequest.html#/.abstract: The account id of the expected bucket owner. If the bucket is owned by a different account, the request will fail with an HTTP 403 (Access Denied) error.

Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectRequest.html#/.name: key
Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectRequest.html#/.abstract: Object key for which the operation was initiated.

Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectRequest.html#/.name: requestPayer
Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectRequest.html#/.abstract: Confirms that the requester knows that they will be charged for the request. Bucket owners need not specify this parameter in their requests. For information about downloading objects from requester pays buckets, see Downloading Objects in Requestor Pays Buckets in the Amazon S3 Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectRequest.html#/.name: versionId
Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectRequest.html#/.abstract: VersionId used to reference a specific version of the object.

Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectOutput.html#/c.name: requestCharged
Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectOutput.html#/c.abstract: If present, indicates that the requester was successfully charged for the request.

Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectOutput.html#/c.name: restoreOutputPath
Classes/AWSS3RestoreObjectOutput.html#/c.abstract: Indicates the path in the provided S3 output location where Select results will be restored to.

Classes/AWSS3RequestProgress.html#/c:obj.name: enabled
Classes/AWSS3RequestProgress.html#/c:obj.abstract: Specifies whether periodic QueryProgress frames should be sent. Valid values: TRUE, FALSE. Default value: FALSE.

Classes/AWSS3RequestPaymentConfiguration.name: payer
Classes/AWSS3RequestPaymentConfiguration.abstract: Specifies who pays for the download and request fees.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationTimeValue.html#/.name: minutes
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationTimeValue.html#/.abstract:
Contains an integer specifying time in minutes.

Valid values: 15 minutes.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationTime.html#/c:obj.name: status
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationTime.html#/c:obj.abstract: Specifies whether the replication time is enabled.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationTime.html#/c:obj.name: time
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationTime.html#/c:obj.abstract: A container specifying the time by which replication should be complete for all objects and operations on objects.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRuleFilter.html#.name: AND
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRuleFilter.html#.abstract:
A container for specifying rule filters. The filters determine the subset of objects to which the rule applies. This element is required only if you specify more than one filter. For example:

  • If you specify both a Prefix and a Tag filter, wrap these filters in an And tag.

  • If you specify a filter based on multiple tags, wrap the Tag elements in an And tag.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRuleFilter.html#.name: prefix
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRuleFilter.html#.abstract: An object key name prefix that identifies the subset of objects to which the rule applies.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRuleFilter.html#.name: tag
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRuleFilter.html#.abstract:
A container for specifying a tag key and value.

The rule applies only to objects that have the tag in their tag set.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRuleAndOperator..name: prefix
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRuleAndOperator..abstract: An object key name prefix that identifies the subset of objects to which the rule applies.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRuleAndOperator..name: tags
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRuleAndOperator..abstract: An array of tags containing key and value pairs.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.name: deleteMarkerReplication
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.abstract:
Specifies whether Amazon S3 replicates the delete markers. If you specify a Filter, you must specify this element. However, in the latest version of replication configuration (when Filter is specified), Amazon S3 doesn’t replicate delete markers. Therefore, the DeleteMarkerReplication element can contain only <Status>Disabled</Status>. For an example configuration, see Basic Rule Configuration.

If you don’t specify the Filter element, Amazon S3 assumes that the replication configuration is the earlier version, V1. In the earlier version, Amazon S3 handled replication of delete markers differently. For more information, see Backward Compatibility.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.name: destination
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.abstract: A container for information about the replication destination and its configurations including enabling the S3 Replication Time Control (S3 RTC).

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.name: filter
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.abstract: A filter that identifies the subset of objects to which the replication rule applies. A Filter must specify exactly one Prefix, Tag, or an And child element.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.name: identifier
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.abstract: A unique identifier for the rule. The maximum value is 255 characters.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.name: prefix
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.abstract: An object key name prefix that identifies the object or objects to which the rule applies. The maximum prefix length is 1,024 characters. To include all objects in a bucket, specify an empty string.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.name: priority
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.abstract:
The priority associated with the rule. If you specify multiple rules in a replication configuration, Amazon S3 prioritizes the rules to prevent conflicts when filtering. If two or more rules identify the same object based on a specified filter, the rule with higher priority takes precedence. For example:

  • Same object quality prefix-based filter criteria if prefixes you specified in multiple rules overlap

  • Same object qualify tag-based filter criteria specified in multiple rules

For more information, see Replication in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.name: sourceSelectionCriteria
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationRule.html#/c:obj.abstract: A container that describes additional filters for identifying the source objects that you want to replicate. You can choose to enable or disable the replication of these objects. Currently, Amazon S3 supports only the filter that you can specify for objects created with server-side encryption using a customer master key (CMK) stored in AWS Key Management Service (SSE-KMS).

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationConfiguration.ht.name: role
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationConfiguration.ht.abstract: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) role that Amazon S3 assumes when replicating objects. For more information, see How to Set Up Replication in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3ReplicationConfiguration.ht.name: rules
Classes/AWSS3ReplicationConfiguration.ht.abstract: A container for one or more replication rules. A replication configuration must have at least one rule and can contain a maximum of 1,000 rules.

Classes/AWSS3RedirectAllRequestsTo.html#.name: hostName
Classes/AWSS3RedirectAllRequestsTo.html#.abstract: Name of the host where requests are redirected.

Classes/AWSS3RedirectAllRequestsTo.html#.name: protocols
Classes/AWSS3RedirectAllRequestsTo.html#.abstract: Protocol to use when redirecting requests. The default is the protocol that is used in the original request.

Classes/AWSS3Redirect.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.name: hostName
Classes/AWSS3Redirect.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.abstract: The host name to use in the redirect request.

Classes/AWSS3Redirect.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.name: httpRedirectCode
Classes/AWSS3Redirect.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.abstract: The HTTP redirect code to use on the response. Not required if one of the siblings is present.

Classes/AWSS3Redirect.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.name: protocols
Classes/AWSS3Redirect.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.abstract: Protocol to use when redirecting requests. The default is the protocol that is used in the original request.

Classes/AWSS3Redirect.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.name: replaceKeyPrefixWith
Classes/AWSS3Redirect.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.abstract: The object key prefix to use in the redirect request. For example, to redirect requests for all pages with prefix docs/ (objects in the docs/ folder) to documents/, you can set a condition block with KeyPrefixEquals set to docs/ and in the Redirect set ReplaceKeyPrefixWith to /documents. Not required if one of the siblings is present. Can be present only if ReplaceKeyWith is not provided.

Classes/AWSS3Redirect.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.name: replaceKeyWith

This header can be used as a message integrity check to verify that the data is the same data that was originally sent. Although it is optional, we recommend using the Content-MD5 mechanism as an end-to-end integrity check. For more information about REST request authentication, see REST Authentication.

Classes/AWSS3PutObjectRequest.html#/c:ob.name: SSECustomerKeyMD5

Classes/AWSS3PutObjectRequest.html#/c:ob.name: SSEKMSEncryptionContext
Classes/AWSS3PutObjectRequest.html#/c:ob.abstract: Specifies the AWS KMS Encryption Context to use for object encryption. The value of this header is a base64-encoded UTF-8 string holding JSON with the encryption context key-value pairs.

Classes/AWSS3PutObjectRequest.html#/c:ob.name: SSEKMSKeyId
Classes/AWSS3PutObjectRequest.html#/c:ob.abstract:
If x-amz-server-side-encryption is present and has the value of aws:kms, this header specifies the ID of the AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) symmetrical customer managed customer master key (CMK) that was used for the object.

If the value of x-amz-server-side-encryption is aws:kms, this header specifies the ID of the symmetric customer managed AWS KMS CMK that will be used for the object. If you specify x-amz-server-side-encryption:aws:kms, but do not provide x-amz-server-side-encryption-aws-kms-key-id, Amazon S3 uses the AWS managed CMK in AWS to protect the data.

Classes/AWSS3PutObjectRequest.html#/c:ob.name: serverSideEncryption

Amazon S3 on Outposts only uses the OUTPOSTS Storage Class. For more information, see Storage Classes in the Amazon S3 Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3PutObjectRequest.html#/c:ob.name: websiteRedirectLocation
Classes/AWSS3PutObjectRequest.html#/c:ob.abstract:
If the bucket is configured as a website, redirects requests for this object to another object in the same bucket or to an external URL. Amazon S3 stores the value of this header in the object metadata. For information about object metadata, see Object Key and Metadata.

In the following example, the request header sets the redirect to an object (anotherPage.html) in the same bucket:

x-amz-website-redirect-location: /anotherPage.html

In the following example, the request header sets the object redirect to another website:

x-amz-website-redirect-location: http://www.example.com/

For more information about website hosting in Amazon S3, see Hosting Websites on Amazon S3 and How to Configure Website Page Redirects.

Classes/AWSS3PutObjectOutput.html#/c:obj.name: expiration

Classes/AWSS3PutObjectOutput.html#/c:obj.name: SSEKMSEncryptionContext

Classes/AWSS3PutObjectOutput.html#/c:obj.name: SSEKMSKeyId

Classes/AWSS3PutObjectOutput.html#/c:obj.name: serverSideEncryption
Classes/AWSS3PutObjectOutput.html#/c:obj.abstract: If you specified server-side encryption either with an AWS KMS customer master key (CMK) or Amazon S3-managed encryption key in your PUT request, the response includes this header. Classes/AWSS3PublicAccessBlockConfigurat.name: blockPublicAcls
Classes/AWSS3PublicAccessBlockConfigurat.abstract:
Specifies whether Amazon S3 should block public access control lists (ACLs) for this bucket and objects in this bucket. Setting this element to TRUE causes the following behavior:

  • PUT Bucket acl and PUT Object acl calls fail if the specified ACL is public.

  • PUT Object calls fail if the request includes a public ACL.

  • PUT Bucket calls fail if the request includes a public ACL.

Enabling this setting doesn’t affect existing policies or ACLs.

Classes/AWSS3PublicAccessBlockConfigurat.name: blockPublicPolicy
Classes/AWSS3PublicAccessBlockConfigurat.abstract:
Specifies whether Amazon S3 should block public bucket policies for this bucket. Setting this element to TRUE causes Amazon S3 to reject calls to PUT Bucket policy if the specified bucket policy allows public access.

Enabling this setting doesn’t affect existing bucket policies.

Classes/AWSS3PublicAccessBlockConfigurat.name: ignorePublicAcls
Classes/AWSS3PublicAccessBlockConfigurat.abstract:
Specifies whether Amazon S3 should ignore public ACLs for this bucket and objects in this bucket. Setting this element to TRUE causes Amazon S3 to ignore all public ACLs on this bucket and objects in this bucket.

Enabling this setting doesn’t affect the persistence of any existing ACLs and doesn’t prevent new public ACLs from being set.

Classes/AWSS3PublicAccessBlockConfigurat.name: restrictPublicBuckets
Classes/AWSS3PublicAccessBlockConfigurat.abstract:
Specifies whether Amazon S3 should restrict public bucket policies for this bucket. Setting this element to TRUE restricts access to this bucket to only AWS services and authorized users within this account if the bucket has a public policy.

Enabling this setting doesn’t affect previously stored bucket policies, except that public and cross-account access within any public bucket policy, including non-public delegation to specific accounts, is blocked.

Classes/AWSS3Object.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS.name: ETag
Classes/AWSS3Object.html#/c:objc(cs)AWSS.abstract:
The entity tag is a hash of the object. The ETag reflects changes only to the contents of an object, not its metadata. The ETag may or may not be an MD5 digest of the object data. Whether or not it is depends on how the object was created and how it is encrypted as described below:

  • Objects created by the PUT Object, POST Object, or Copy operation, or through the AWS Management Console, and are encrypted by SSE-S3 or plaintext, have ETags that are an MD5 digest of their object data.

  • Objects created by the PUT Object, POST Object, or Copy operation, or through the AWS Management Console, and are encrypted by SSE-C or SSE-KMS, have ETags that are not an MD5 digest of their object data.

  • If an object is created by either the Multipart Upload or Part Copy operation, the ETag is not an MD5 digest, regardless of the method of encryption.

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsRequest.html#/c:ob.name: bucket
Classes/AWSS3ListPartsRequest.html#/c:ob.abstract:
The name of the bucket to which the parts are being uploaded.

When using this API with an access point, you must direct requests to the access point hostname. The access point hostname takes the form AccessPointName-AccountId.s3-accesspoint.Region.amazonaws.com. When using this operation with an access point through the AWS SDKs, you provide the access point ARN in place of the bucket name. For more information about access point ARNs, see Using Access Points in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

When using this API with Amazon S3 on Outposts, you must direct requests to the S3 on Outposts hostname. The S3 on Outposts hostname takes the form AccessPointName-AccountId.outpostID.s3-outposts.Region.amazonaws.com. When using this operation using S3 on Outposts through the AWS SDKs, you provide the Outposts bucket ARN in place of the bucket name. For more information about S3 on Outposts ARNs, see Using S3 on Outposts in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: abortDate
Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.abstract:
If the bucket has a lifecycle rule configured with an action to abort incomplete multipart uploads and the prefix in the lifecycle rule matches the object name in the request, then the response includes this header indicating when the initiated multipart upload will become eligible for abort operation. For more information, see Aborting Incomplete Multipart Uploads Using a Bucket Lifecycle Policy.

The response will also include the x-amz-abort-rule-id header that will provide the ID of the lifecycle configuration rule that defines this action.

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: abortRuleId
Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.abstract: This header is returned along with the x-amz-abort-date header. It identifies applicable lifecycle configuration rule that defines the action to abort incomplete multipart uploads.

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: bucket
Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.abstract: The name of the bucket to which the multipart upload was initiated.

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: initiator
Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.abstract: Container element that identifies who initiated the multipart upload. If the initiator is an AWS account, this element provides the same information as the Owner element. If the initiator is an IAM User, this element provides the user ARN and display name.

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: isTruncated
Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.abstract: Indicates whether the returned list of parts is truncated. A true value indicates that the list was truncated. A list can be truncated if the number of parts exceeds the limit returned in the MaxParts element.

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: key
Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.abstract: Object key for which the multipart upload was initiated.

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: maxParts
Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.abstract: Maximum number of parts that were allowed in the response.

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: nextPartNumberMarker
Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.abstract: When a list is truncated, this element specifies the last part in the list, as well as the value to use for the part-number-marker request parameter in a subsequent request.

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: owner
Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.abstract: Container element that identifies the object owner, after the object is created. If multipart upload is initiated by an IAM user, this element provides the parent account ID and display name.

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: partNumberMarker
Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.abstract: When a list is truncated, this element specifies the last part in the list, as well as the value to use for the part-number-marker request parameter in a subsequent request.

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: parts

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: requestCharged

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: storageClass

Classes/AWSS3ListPartsOutput.html#/c:obj.name: uploadId

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.name: bucket
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.abstract:
Bucket name to list.

When using this API with an access point, you must direct requests to the access point hostname. The access point hostname takes the form AccessPointName-AccountId.s3-accesspoint.Region.amazonaws.com. When using this operation with an access point through the AWS SDKs, you provide the access point ARN in place of the bucket name. For more information about access point ARNs, see Using Access Points in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

When using this API with Amazon S3 on Outposts, you must direct requests to the S3 on Outposts hostname. The S3 on Outposts hostname takes the form AccessPointName-AccountId.outpostID.s3-outposts.Region.amazonaws.com. When using this operation using S3 on Outposts through the AWS SDKs, you provide the Outposts bucket ARN in place of the bucket name. For more information about S3 on Outposts ARNs, see Using S3 on Outposts in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.name: continuationToken
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.abstract: ContinuationToken indicates Amazon S3 that the list is being continued on this bucket with a token. ContinuationToken is obfuscated and is not a real key.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.name: delimiter
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.abstract: A delimiter is a character you use to group keys.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.name: encodingType
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.abstract: Encoding type used by Amazon S3 to encode object keys in the response.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.name: expectedBucketOwner
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.abstract: The account id of the expected bucket owner. If the bucket is owned by a different account, the request will fail with an HTTP 403 (Access Denied) error.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.name: fetchOwner
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.abstract: The owner field is not present in listV2 by default, if you want to return owner field with each key in the result then set the fetch owner field to true.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.name: maxKeys
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.abstract: Sets the maximum number of keys returned in the response. By default the API returns up to 1,000 key names. The response might contain fewer keys but will never contain more.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.name: prefix
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.abstract: Limits the response to keys that begin with the specified prefix.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.name: requestPayer
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.abstract: Confirms that the requester knows that she or he will be charged for the list objects request in V2 style. Bucket owners need not specify this parameter in their requests.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.name: startAfter
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Request.html#/.abstract: StartAfter is where you want Amazon S3 to start listing from. Amazon S3 starts listing after this specified key. StartAfter can be any key in the bucket.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.name: commonPrefixes
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.abstract:
All of the keys rolled up into a common prefix count as a single return when calculating the number of returns.

A response can contain CommonPrefixes only if you specify a delimiter.

CommonPrefixes contains all (if there are any) keys between Prefix and the next occurrence of the string specified by a delimiter.

CommonPrefixes lists keys that act like subdirectories in the directory specified by Prefix.

For example, if the prefix is notes/ and the delimiter is a slash (/) as in notes/summer/july, the common prefix is notes/summer/. All of the keys that roll up into a common prefix count as a single return when calculating the number of returns.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.name: continuationToken
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.abstract: If ContinuationToken was sent with the request, it is included in the response.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.name: delimiter
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.abstract: Causes keys that contain the same string between the prefix and the first occurrence of the delimiter to be rolled up into a single result element in the CommonPrefixes collection. These rolled-up keys are not returned elsewhere in the response. Each rolled-up result counts as only one return against the MaxKeys value.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.name: encodingType
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.abstract:
Encoding type used by Amazon S3 to encode object key names in the XML response.

If you specify the encoding-type request parameter, Amazon S3 includes this element in the response, and returns encoded key name values in the following response elements:

Delimiter, Prefix, Key, and StartAfter.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.name: isTruncated
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.abstract: Set to false if all of the results were returned. Set to true if more keys are available to return. If the number of results exceeds that specified by MaxKeys, all of the results might not be returned.

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.name: keyCount
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.abstract: KeyCount is the number of keys returned with this request. KeyCount will always be less than equals to MaxKeys field. Say you ask for 50 keys, your result will include less than equals 50 keys

Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.name: maxKeys
Classes/AWSS3ListObjectsV2Output.html#/c.abstract: Sets the maximum number of keys returned in the response. By default the API returns up to 1,000 key names. The response might contain fewer keys but will never contain more.

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.name: bucket
Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.abstract:
The name of the bucket to which the multipart upload was initiated.

When using this API with an access point, you must direct requests to the access point hostname. The access point hostname takes the form AccessPointName-AccountId.s3-accesspoint.Region.amazonaws.com. When using this operation with an access point through the AWS SDKs, you provide the access point ARN in place of the bucket name. For more information about access point ARNs, see Using Access Points in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

When using this API with Amazon S3 on Outposts, you must direct requests to the S3 on Outposts hostname. The S3 on Outposts hostname takes the form AccessPointName-AccountId.outpostID.s3-outposts.Region.amazonaws.com. When using this operation using S3 on Outposts through the AWS SDKs, you provide the Outposts bucket ARN in place of the bucket name. For more information about S3 on Outposts ARNs, see Using S3 on Outposts in the Amazon Simple Storage Service Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.name: delimiter
Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.abstract:
Character you use to group keys.

All keys that contain the same string between the prefix, if specified, and the first occurrence of the delimiter after the prefix are grouped under a single result element, CommonPrefixes. If you don’t specify the prefix parameter, then the substring starts at the beginning of the key. The keys that are grouped under CommonPrefixes result element are not returned elsewhere in the response.

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.name: encodingType
Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.abstract: Requests Amazon S3 to encode the object keys in the response and specifies the encoding method to use. An object key may contain any Unicode character; however, XML 1.0 parser cannot parse some characters, such as characters with an ASCII value from 0 to 10. For characters that are not supported in XML 1.0, you can add this parameter to request that Amazon S3 encode the keys in the response.

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.name: expectedBucketOwner
Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.abstract: The account id of the expected bucket owner. If the bucket is owned by a different account, the request will fail with an HTTP 403 (Access Denied) error.

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.name: keyMarker
Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.abstract:
Together with upload-id-marker, this parameter specifies the multipart upload after which listing should begin.

If upload-id-marker is not specified, only the keys lexicographically greater than the specified key-marker will be included in the list.

If upload-id-marker is specified, any multipart uploads for a key equal to the key-marker might also be included, provided those multipart uploads have upload IDs lexicographically greater than the specified upload-id-marker.

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.name: maxUploads
Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.abstract: Sets the maximum number of multipart uploads, from 1 to 1,000, to return in the response body. 1,000 is the maximum number of uploads that can be returned in a response.

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.name: prefix
Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.abstract: Lists in-progress uploads only for those keys that begin with the specified prefix. You can use prefixes to separate a bucket into different grouping of keys. (You can think of using prefix to make groups in the same way you’d use a folder in a file system.)

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.name: uploadIdMarker
Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsRequest.abstract: Together with key-marker, specifies the multipart upload after which listing should begin. If key-marker is not specified, the upload-id-marker parameter is ignored. Otherwise, any multipart uploads for a key equal to the key-marker might be included in the list only if they have an upload ID lexicographically greater than the specified upload-id-marker.

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsOutput..name: bucket
Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsOutput..abstract: The name of the bucket to which the multipart upload was initiated.

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsOutput..name: commonPrefixes
Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsOutput..abstract: If you specify a delimiter in the request, then the result returns each distinct key prefix containing the delimiter in a CommonPrefixes element. The distinct key prefixes are returned in the Prefix child element.

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsOutput..abstract: Contains the delimiter you specified in the request. If you don’t specify a delimiter in your request, this element is absent from the response.

Delimiter, KeyMarker, Prefix, NextKeyMarker, Key.

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsOutput..name: isTruncated
Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsOutput..abstract: Indicates whether the returned list of multipart uploads is truncated. A value of true indicates that the list was truncated. The list can be truncated if the number of multipart uploads exceeds the limit allowed or specified by max uploads.

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsOutput..name: keyMarker
Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsOutput..abstract: The key at or after which the listing began.

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsOutput..name: prefix

Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsOutput..name: uploads
Classes/AWSS3ListMultipartUploadsOutput..abstract: Container for elements related to a particular multipart upload. A response can contain zero or more Upload elements.
